Milestone One¶

Introduction¶

Objective:¶

  • Train a simple GBM model, and interpret what the underlying logic of the model is using SHAP.

Workflow:¶

  • Load data
  • Train model
  • Create SHAP explainer
  • Use SHAP explainer to generate importance plots, summary plots, and force plots
  • Evaluate if the reasoning of the model makes sense

Importance to Project:¶

  • to determine any biases underlying a model we need to deeply understand our models.
  • we need to know more than just the most important features: we need to understand how they interact, and what the impact of different feature values can be on a prediction.
  • The workflow here helps us answer these questions.

Resources:¶

  • https://christophm.github.io/interpretable-ml-book/shapley.html
  • https://christophm.github.io/interpretable-ml-book/shap.html (particularly 5.10.5, 5.10.6, 5.10.7, 5.10.8, 5.10.9 on force plots
  • https://github.com/slundberg/shap/blob/master/notebooks/tree_explainer/tree_shap_paper/Figure%204%20-%20Supervised%20Clustering%20Adult%20Census%20Data.ipynb
  • https://github.com/slundberg/shap/blob/master/notebooks/tree_explainer/Front%20page%20example%20(XGBoost).ipynb

"""Our goal for this task is to interpret a machine learning model using SHAP. The modelling itself is not the main focus of
the task. In the interests of providing an engaging example, the model we are building is a GBM which predicts the 
number of future covid-19 cases per country
from features available in the present.

Based on the default parameters, the target variable is the new daily COVID-19 cases 14 days from the date of feature collection. 

You could pick a different window to 14 days by changing the day_window parameter.

To determine the model's performance, we use a date-based train/test split. You could pick a different date window by changing the training and testing parameters below.

The dataset is pulled from Our World In Data's github repository, so it should be updated daily.

For visualization purposes, we pull out the final day of the testing set and select only countries with fewer than 1000 cases per day.

"""

training_start_date = pd.to_datetime('1 Apr 2020')
training_end_date = pd.to_datetime('15 May 2020')
testing_start_date = pd.to_datetime('15 May 2020')
testing_end_date = pd.to_datetime('1 Jun 2020')
day_window = 14
target_var = 'new_cases_in_%s_days' % day_window
In [4]:
def get_latest_covid_data():
    covid_data = pd.read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/owid/covid-19-data/master/public/data/owid-covid-data.csv') #dataset of COVID occurrence/death by country by date
    covid_data = covid_data[~covid_data['location'].isin(['World','International'])] #filter out these special values
    covid_data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(covid_data['date']) #apply datetime transformation
    return covid_data

def join_features_to_target(covid_data, window=day_window):
    #our aim is to predict new covid cases as of 14 days from the date the features are from.
    
    features = covid_data.copy()
    
    target_data = covid_data.copy().rename({'new_cases':target_var}, axis=1) 
    target_data = target_data[['location','date',target_var]]

    features['anchor_date'] = (features['date']+pd.Timedelta(day_window, unit='d')).astype('int64')
    target_data['anchor_date'] = (target_data['date']).astype('int64')
    dataset = pd.merge(features, target_data, on=('location','anchor_date'),how='inner',suffixes=['','_future'])
    dataset = dataset.sort_values(['location','date'])
    return dataset, target_var
    
def train_test_split_by_time(dataset):
    train = dataset[dataset['date'].between(training_start_date,
                                           training_end_date)].set_index(['location','date'])
    test = dataset[dataset['date'].between(testing_start_date,
                                          testing_end_date)].set_index(['location','date'])
    return train, test

covid_data = get_latest_covid_data()
dataset, target_var = join_features_to_target(covid_data)
train, test = train_test_split_by_time(dataset)
visualization = test.reset_index()[(test.reset_index()['date']==test.reset_index()['date'].max()) &
                               (test.reset_index()[target_var]<1000)].set_index(['location','date'])

1.4 Create relevant plots, explain model's prediction on one example and on multiple examples¶

Before we dive into plotting SHAP values are, here is a brief recap from the reading provided above.

"The goal of SHAP is to explain the prediction of an instance x by computing the contribution of each feature to the prediction." (https://christophm.github.io/interpretable-ml-book/shap.html).

  • Below you can see a visualization of SHAP values for a single model prediction.
  • The starting point is the base (expected) value. This is a constant across all rows.
  • From this starting point, the red forces (positive SHAP values) battle the blue forces (negative SHAP values) to push the final prediction up or down respectively. Where they meet is the model's prediction.
  • A positive SHAP value means that for this prediction, the corresponding feature pushes the prediction up by approximately the SHAP value. A negative SHAP value means that for this prediction, the corresponding feature pushes the prediction down.
  • The output value is higher than the base value, which reflects that the positive SHAP values outweigh the negative SHAP values for this row.

All global explanations using SHAP are aggregations of these prediction-level local explanations.

In [10]:
"""
Create a SHAP summary plot to understand what the model's reasoning is globally on the train set
 - use shap.TreeExplainer to generate an explanation object for your GBM
 - use explainer.shap_values to generate SHAP values for the training set
 - use shap.summary_plot to generate a plot explaining the model's predictions
 - understand and reflect on the underlying reasoning used by the model, based on the summary plot
 
"""


explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(reg)
shap_values = explainer.shap_values(X_train) #make SHAP explanation values
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, X_train)

Setting feature_perturbation = "tree_path_dependent" because no background data was given.

"""
 - Using shap.force_plot on only one row of data, explain the model's reasoning for prediction on that row.
 - In general, the base value is the expected value for the whole training set. If the model's output is lower, it means that the 
 downward pushing forces (blue forces) are stronger than the upward pushing forces (red forces)"""

row_number = 8
shap.force_plot(explainer.expected_value, shap_values_day[row_number,:], X_visualization.iloc[row_number,:]) #explain one row of data
